{
  "texts": [
    "We recognize that an even finer resolution would be required to fully characterize the transition at J 2 /J 1 = 0.51, but due to computational constraints we do not pursue this further here.",
    "Nonetheless, we can safely conclude that the direct transition between the Z ± q AFM ⊕ Z 2 NM phases is first-order for J 2 /J 1 ≲ 0.51, whereas for larger values it becomes a Landau-incompatible continuous transition.",
    "* titas.chanda@physics.iitm.ac.in [1] M. E. J. Newman and G. T. Barkema, Monte Carlo Methods in Statistical Physics (Oxford University Press, Oxford, UK, 1999).",
    "q AFM ⊕ Z2 NM phases at low J2/J1 = 0.505.",
    "The right column illustrates (c) f and (f) df /dx across the low-T transitions at J2/J1 = 0.5, specifically the Z + q FM (T /J1 = 0.03) and QLRO (T /J1 = 0.06) phases into the Z + q AFM ⊕ Z2 NM phase."
  ]
}